---
import Heading from "../../components/Heading.astro";
import Highlight from "../../components/Highlight.astro";
import PageHeader from "../../components/PageHeader.astro";
import Paragraph from "../../components/Paragraph.astro";
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import ImageStep1 from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step1.png";
import ImageStep3a from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step3a.png";
import ImageStep3b from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step3b.png";
import ImageStep3c from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step3c.png";
import ImageStep4a from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step4a.png";
import ImageStep4b from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step4b.png";
import ImageStep5a from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step5a.png";
import ImageStep5b from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step5b.png";
import ImageStep6 from "../../images/portfolio/figma/step6.png";
import ImageWrapper from "../../components/ImageWrapper.astro";
import HorizontalScrollList from "../../layouts/HorizontalScrollList.astro";
import HorizontalScrollItem from "../../layouts/HorizontalScrollItem.astro";
import TextContainer from "../../layouts/TextContainer.astro";
---

<BaseLayout>
  <PageHeader heading="Moving a design system to Figma">
    This case study describes how I moved a design system from Sketch to Figma.
    Specifically, how I obtained management approval, created a new UI kit from
    scratch, and onboarded a team of designers.
  </PageHeader>
  <TextContainer>
    <Heading as="h2" step="1">Convince management</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The first step was to convince management to approve the purchase of
      Figma. The main arguments were lower costs and fewer UI design tools,
      since Figma would not only replace Sketch, but also Axure and InVision.
      However, to strengthen our case, I helped create an extensive comparison
      of Figma and Sketch, which you can see here.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep1}
        alt="A table comparing Figma and Sketch based on support for various features, such as version history, sharing, and platform support."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h2" step="2">Create foundation</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      After gaining approval from management to purchase Figma, it was time to
      lay the foundation for the new UI kit.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      I had read various online articles about people’s experiences with moving
      from Sketch to Figma. A recurring theme was that it wasn’t worth the
      effort to import a UI kit from Sketch and update it. It was better to
      start from scratch.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      So, that’s what I did. I started by creating color styles, text styles,
      and effect styles based on the design system’s design tokens. These would
      serve as the foundation for all the Figma components to be created.
    </Paragraph>
    <Heading as="h2" step="3">Create components</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The next step was to get to work and build the components.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      Over the course of several months, I built 40+ components.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      My main priority was to match the Figma components as much as possible to
      their counterparts in code. That meant they should look the same, be named
      the same (including variants/properties), and be categorized the same way.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      The aim of these efforts was to enable designers and developers to speak
      the same language and thereby collaborate more efficiently. When
      inspecting a mockup, it should be easy for developers to find out which
      components they should use to build the design in code.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep3a}
        alt="Three screenshots from Figma. The first shows a component picker with different component categories, such as “navigation” and “feedback”. The second shows the content of the “forms and input” component category, with components such as “checkbox”, “dropdown”, and “input field”. The third shows a checkbox component with variants for different states, such as checked, unchecked, default, hover, focus, and disabled."
        width="400"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Paragraph>
      Part of creating the components, was utilizing some of Figma’s unique
      features as much as possible.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      These are features that made it worthwhile to move to Figma in the first
      place. Two of the most important ones are highlighted here.
    </Paragraph>
    <Heading as="h3">Component variants</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      Sketch has something similar to component variants. However, you need to
      navigate through nested menus to switch between them. In contrast, Figma
      offers a clear overview with simple menus and toggles for every property.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep3b}
        alt="A screenshot from Figma with a selected “Button” component and a panel with controls for switching between the component's variants and properties."
        width="400"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h3">Interactive components</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The interactive components feature enables you to provide components with
      built-in interactions between their variants. This saves designers a lot
      of time and effort when creating prototypes. I added as many
      hover/press/state/etc. interactions as possible.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep3c}
        alt="A screenshot from Figma showing a component called “Toggle Switch” with prototype interactions set up between the component’s variants based on events such as “Mouse up” and “While Pressing”."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h2" step="4">Add descriptions and documentation links</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      Once I had created all the components, I added two things to them:
      descriptions and links to their pages on the documentation site.
    </Paragraph>
    <Heading as="h3">Descriptions</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The descriptions simply say “Lib” or “Lab”. These terms indicate whether
      or not a component satisfies the Definition of Done (DoD). The DoD is a
      list of requirements related to development, UX, accessibility, process,
      and documentation. New components start out in “Lab” and end up in “Lib”,
      when they satisfy all DoD requirements. As such, these terms are meant to
      signal a certain level of quality.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep4a}
        alt="A screenshot from Figma showing six different “Actions and controls” components. The “Button” component has a popover containing the text “Lib”."
        width="320"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h3">Documentation links</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The documentation links help designers look up a component’s guidelines
      concerning when and how to use it, UX writing, and accessibility. They
      also help developers, by providing them with implementation guidelines,
      example code, and information about the component’s API.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep4b}
        alt="A screenshot from Figma showing a selected Button component and a “View documentation” link in an “Inspect” panel on the right."
        width="320"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h2" step="5">Introduce new UI kit</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      It was now time to inform my fellow product designers that the new UI kit
      was ready and available for use.
    </Paragraph>
    <Heading as="h3">Announcement</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      I announced the availability of the new UI kit on Slack. In the message, I
      explained how to install it, what it contains, and how to get started with
      using its components. I also mentioned a Figma plugin I installed for
      everyone, to make it easy to check for accessible color contrast levels.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep5a}
        alt="A Slack message from Hans Sandberg announcing the availability of the new UI kit."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h3">Video walkthrough</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      Next, I recorded and shared a video wherein I walked through the UI kit’s
      features in detail and explained how to use them.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep5b}
        alt="A Slack message from Hans Sandberg with a video about the new Figma UI kit."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h2" step="6">Create FAQ</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      Next, I added an FAQ about the Figma UI kit to the documentation site. It
      contains much of the same information that I covered in the video
      walkthrough.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      However, I wanted designers to be able to access this information in a
      faster and more convenient way. Also, the FAQ page is better suited to be
      continuously updated.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep6}
        alt="The “Figma FAQ for designers” page of the design system’s documentation site. It features questions divided into sections labelled “General”, “Colors, shadows, and text”,  “Components”, and “Forms”."
        width="600"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h2" step="7">Follow up with designers</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The last step was to follow up with the designers in the weeks following
      the launch of the new UI kit.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      I wanted to hear about their first impressions of both Figma and the UI
      kit and any issues they’d run into. The most important learnings are
      summarized here.
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Import issue" icon="issue">
          Designers that had started migrating, mentioned it wasn’t pain free.
          Their Sketch mockups got pretty messed up when importing them into
          Figma. One designer noted it took him two full weeks to make
          everything look correct again. Sadly, other than encouraging words,
          there wasn’t much I could do to help them through this initial phase.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Not automatically available" icon="block">
          A designer mentioned it was annoying that she had to add the UI kit to
          every new file. This surprised me, as I had expected the UI kit to be
          automatically available in all new files. Apparently, this was a
          setting I had to enable, which I promptly did.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Small bugs" icon="bug">
          Several designers had encountered small bugs in the UI kit. These
          ranged from color and shadow styles not matching our design tokens, to
          components lacking correct responsive behavior. I made an effort to
          correct these mistakes as fast as possible.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Generally happy" icon="happy">
          Although not perfect, Figma and the UI kit made a generally good first
          impression. The designers were excited to start using this new
          industry leading design tool. Some mentioned already not being able to
          live without some of its unique features, such as auto layout.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
  </TextContainer>
</BaseLayout>
